  Window History :- 
                  Before Windows, Microsoft’s operating systems were much simpler. Early computers ran
                  MS-DOS, which showed a black screen where you had to type commands instead of clicking 
                  icons. In 1985, Microsoft released Windows 1.0, a basic graphical user interface (GUI)
                  built on top of DOS, introducing windows, menus, and mouse controls to personal computers. 
                   Windows has added more features.


  Window Areas :-
                * Desktop :
                           The main workspace where files, folders, and shortcuts live.
                           Main screen where icons placed.
                * Taskbar :
                           Bottom strip where start button , time and current running
                           tasks and software placed.

                * Start Menu :
                              It is like a heart of programs it is open when we click open
                              button . The main workspace where files, folders, and shortcuts
                              live ,access applications, settings, and power options.

                * File Explorer :
                                 It is like a cabinet where all file ,folder, partitions
                                 and Documents placed.

                * Setting :
                           We can set every setting like wallpaper , sound and WiFi placed
                           here.

                * Kernel :
                          It is like internal brain which is invisible and control hardware.

                * Search :
                          Quickly find applications, files, folders, and system settings by using
                          keywords .

                * Task View :
                            Allows you to see all currently open windows and quickly switch between
                            them.

                * Pinned Applications and Folders :
                                                   Your most used applications and folders can be pinned
                                                    here.

                * Network and audio setting :
                                             It use to access network and sound settings.

                * Date and time :
                                 Opens up to a full calendar. Date and time settings can be accessed
                                  here, too .


                * Notifications :
                                 Displays computer or application notifications. Network and other settings
                                  can also be accessed .

                * Microsoft Store:
                                   The native Windows application for installing trusted applications.

                * Windows Update:
                                   A built-in update tool that helps keep your OS, native apps, and security
                                    features up to date .

                * Control Panel:
                                 The legacy management interface that provides access to system configuration
                                 options .

                * Task Manager:
                                A Windows tool for monitoring what is happening on your system in real time.

                * Windows Security:
                                  The central dashboard for managing Windows built-in security tools .

                * Windows Defender Firewall:
                                            The firewall designed to help protect your system from unauthorized
                                             network traffic .


   Basic CMD Commands :-
                        * cd ( pwd ) :
                              To check current dir location.

                        * dir ( ls ) :
                               To list contents in folder .

                        * dir /a ( ls -la) :
                                            List in detail.

                        * cd folder name :
                                          To change directory or folder.

                         * cd .. :
                                   To change directory one step back.

                         * cls :
                               To clear screen.


                        * ipconfig :
                                    To check ip address.

                        * tasklist(ps aux) :
                                    List of all running task or processes.

                        * taskkill /PID 1234 :
                                              To terminate task from tasklist.

                        * systeminfo (uname -a) :
                                      window version and PC info.

                        * whoami :
                                  Who user logged in.

                        * type nul file.txt:
                                            To create a file.

                        * type filename.txt:
                                            To read content from file.

                        * copy file.txt file2.txt :
                                                   To copy a file.

                        * del filename.txt :
                                            To delete a file .

                        * mkdir New folder :
                                            To create a folder.

                        * rmdir Folder name :
                                             To delete folder.

                        * ver :
                                window version.

                        * tracert <google.com> :
                                                To check data is passing from which
                                                route.

                        * netstat -ano :
                                        To check which port is open and which program
                                        use which port (ano) mean show all.


                        * ping <google.com> :
                                             To check internet.

                        * nslookup <google.com> :
                                                 To check the domain of ip.

                        * \ :
                             To locate in window.

                        * / :
                             To locate in Linux.


